{"_path":"/articles/aws-solution-architect-2-2","_dir":"articles","_draft":false,"_partial":false,"_locale":"","title":"Who Owns What in the Cloud?","description":"Consistency and standards are important for building a unified design language and help the user know what to expect from our product and how to use it. However, this does not mean sacrificing the user experience. In this sense, the context and needs of our users are priorities when developing our solutions.","tutor":1,"slidesUrl":"https://github.com/AherRahul/portfolio-v1/blob/main/content/articles/aws-solution-architect-exam-guide.md","dateModified":"2024-05-22","datePublished":"2024-05-22","showOnArticles":false,"courseName":"aws-solution-architect","topics":["system-design","aws","lld"],"videoUrl":"https://www.youtube.com/embed/izQlU1sZkNg?si=q_GceoOp1N6nWdNZ","readingTime":{"text":"5 min read","minutes":4.27,"time":256200,"words":854},"body":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tag":"h2","props":{"id":"who-owns-what-in-the-cloud-understanding-aws-shared-responsibility-model"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Who Owns What in the Cloud? Understanding AWS Shared Responsibility Model"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As businesses embrace the cloud, one question often arises: "},{"type":"element","tag":"strong","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Who is responsible for what?"}]},{"type":"text","value":" When using cloud services like AWS, the answer isn’t always straightforward. The "},{"type":"element","tag":"strong","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"AWS Shared Responsibility Model"}]},{"type":"text","value":" outlines the division of responsibilities between AWS and its customers, ensuring clarity about security, compliance, and management."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This blog unpacks the AWS Shared Responsibility Model and explains how it works, giving you the insights needed to secure your cloud-based workloads effectively."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h2","props":{"id":"the-aws-shared-responsibility-model-an-overview"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The AWS Shared Responsibility Model: An Overview"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In traditional IT environments, organizations manage and control everything: hardware, networking, data security, and more. However, in the cloud, responsibilities are shared between the "},{"type":"element","tag":"strong","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"cloud service provider (AWS)"}]},{"type":"text","value":" and the "},{"type":"element","tag":"strong","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"customer"}]},{"type":"text","value":"."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"AWS describes its shared responsibility model as:"},{"type":"element","tag":"br","props":{},"children":[]},{"type":"text","value":"\n**“Security OF the cloud” is AWS’s responsibility, while "},{"type":"element","tag":"strong","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"“Security IN the cloud” is the customer’s responsibility."}]}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h3","props":{"id":"what-does-this-mean"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"What Does This Mean?"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"ul","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"li","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"strong","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"AWS Responsibility:"}]},{"type":"text","value":" AWS takes care of the physical infrastructure, networking, and foundational services required to run cloud resources."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"li","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"strong","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Customer Responsibility:"}]},{"type":"text","value":" Customers are responsible for managing their data, applications, operating systems, and security settings."}]}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h